THE WARDEN'S AUDITION
THE HUNGER
The Winking Skeever was quiet in the deep hours of night. Most of the city slept, trusting in stone walls and Imperial discipline to keep them safe. They were wrong.
Alfonso lay in his bed, staring at the ceiling. The hunger gnawed at him—a deep, demanding need that went beyond mere sustenance. The infection was settling into his bones, rewriting what he was on a fundamental level.
He rose silently, dressed in dark clothes, and slipped out through the window.
The streets of Solitude at night were beautiful in their own way. Moonlight painted the clean stone in silver, and the distant sound of the sea provided a constant, rhythmic backdrop. Alfonso moved through the shadows with the ease of someone who'd spent years learning to go unnoticed.
The market district was his destination. Specifically, a small clothing shop he'd spotted during their arrival—Radiant Raiment's lesser competitor, a boutique that catered to those with taste but not quite enough coin for the Altmer sisters' prices.
The shop was closed, but light still flickered in the back room. Someone was working late.
Alfonso waited, patient as stone, watching the patterns of the guard patrols. When the opening came, he moved to the door and knocked.
The woman who answered was Dunmer, like him. She was tall, her dark hair falling in waves around a face that managed to be both elegant and morbid. Her eyes held a dark curiosity that spoke of someone who found beauty in unexpected places. She wore black velvet and silver jewelry that caught the moonlight.
"We're closed," she said, her tone curious and engaged.
"I noticed your window display," Alfonso said, his voice smooth. "The leather work. It's exceptional. Far better than what I've seen elsewhere in the city."
Her expression shifted—surprise, then pleasure at the recognition. "You have an eye for quality. Most people in this city wouldn't know fine craftsmanship if it bit them."
"I'm not most people."
She smiled. It was a dangerous smile, the kind that promised interesting complications. "A Dunmer in Solitude who appreciates dark aesthetics and fine leather? I need to hear more about this."
She opened the door wider. "Come in. If you're serious about a purchase, I'll show you something special."
Alfonso stepped inside, and the predator's smile remained cold and calculating.
An hour later, he emerged wearing a magnificent black leather outfit—perfectly tailored, with layers and a high collar that would protect his skin from sunlight while still looking like a statement of fashion rather than necessity. The woman had been skilled with her hands in more ways than one.
"The Lonely Troll," she suggested, still flushed and animated. "There's a bard tonight who's supposed to be excellent. We could—"
"I'd love to," Alfonso said, and meant it. The hunger was building, but it could wait. The anticipation would make it sweeter.
The tavern was exactly what its name suggested—a dive on the docks where sailors and dockworkers drank cheap ale and told lies about their exploits. The bard was mediocre at best, but the woman seemed to enjoy herself, and Alfonso played the part of the attentive companion perfectly.
When the evening wound down, she leaned close. "Your place?"
"I'm staying at an inn," Alfonso said with a regretful smile. "Shared accommodations. Not exactly private."
She bit her lip. "I have a rule about bringing people back to my place on the first night."
"A wise rule," Alfonso agreed. He stood, offering his hand. "Perhaps we should call it an evening then. Though I hate to see it end."
She looked at him, at the elegant leather he wore, at the way the lamplight caught his features. She'd spent the whole evening with a handsome, cultured Dunmer man who shared her interests and made her laugh. The rule suddenly seemed very negotiable.
"Do you trust me?" Alfonso asked, his voice low and intimate.
"Yes," she whispered.
"Then come with me. I know a place."
He led her to the docks, to a quiet section where the warehouses created pockets of shadow and the sound of the waves covered other sounds. She followed willingly, excitement and attraction overriding her usual caution.
What happened next was efficient, methodical, and complete.
When Alfonso returned to the Winking Skeever in the hours before dawn, the new leather outfit remained immaculate, clean of any evidence. He'd fed. Truly fed. And the hunger, for now, was satisfied.

Orion's hunt was simpler but no less effective.
The homeless man was easy to find—there were always lost souls in cities this size, people who'd been broken by war or madness or simple bad luck. This one was huddled near the market, muttering to himself about dragons and darkness and the end of days.
"Friend," Orion said gently, crouching beside him. "You look cold. Hungry."
The man's eyes focused on him with difficulty. "Dragons," he muttered. "They're coming back. I seen it. In my dreams."
"I believe you," Orion said. "Come with me. There's a place near the docks where it's warmer. I'll get you some food."
The man followed, docile as a child. Orion led him down to the warehouse district, to a section of the wooden dock itself where the planks were old and loose and the shadows were deep.
"Wait here," Orion said. "I'll be right back with something warm."
The man nodded, settling down against a piling, already half-asleep.
Orion struck fast. The man barely registered what was happening before the vampire's fangs found his throat. He tried to cry out, but Orion's hand covered his mouth, iron-strong.
The feeding consumed him. The hunger drove him to drain the man completely, and when he finally pulled away, the body in his arms was cold and still.
Dead.
He worked quickly, prying up several loose boards in the dock itself and stuffing the body into the space beneath, into the dark water that lapped at the pilings. The boards went back into place easily, and in the darkness, the disturbance remained invisible.
He walked back to the Winking Skeever as the first hints of dawn touched the eastern sky, his new strength coursing through him like fire.
Behind him, smoke began to rise from the docks.

Ja'ha left the inn entirely.
She'd spent the night wandering the streets of Solitude, confusion warring with the new instincts that drove her. The infection had changed her, made her something between what she'd been and what she was becoming.
The city felt wrong. Too many people. Too much noise. Too much life pressing in from all sides.
She thought of the vampire in Falkreath. Valerius Caelus. He'd understood what she was becoming. He'd known the hunger, the thirst, the terrible clarity that came with undeath.
And he'd offered her a place. A purpose.
By the time the sun rose, Ja'ha was already miles outside the city, following the road toward Morthal. Toward Valerius. Toward understanding.
The Obsidian Lanterns had lost a member, and the remaining party members would discover this absence soon.
THE MORNING AFTER
Davinia woke to sunlight streaming through the window of the room she shared with Danica. The priestess was already awake, sitting by the window and watching the city come to life below.
"Morning," Davinia said, stretching.
Danica turned, and her smile was radiant. "Good morning. I was thinking..."
"Yes?"
"Could we go to the docks? I know we have the audience tonight, but I'd love to see the ships. I've never been this close to the sea before."
Davinia couldn't have refused that smile if she'd wanted to. "Of course. Let's go."
The docks were alive with activity—sailors hauling cargo, merchants haggling over prices, gulls wheeling overhead in the bright morning air. Danica stood at the edge of a pier, breathing in the salt air with obvious delight.
"It's beautiful," she said.
"You're beautiful," Davinia replied before she could stop herself.
Davinia blushed, but before she could respond, shouts erupted from further down the dock.
"Fire! FIRE!"
Flames had erupted from one of the warehouse sections, spreading fast across the old, dry wood. A fisherman was trapped, surrounded by fire on three sides and the water on the fourth.
Davinia moved on instinct, running toward the flames. But as she got close, something happened. The crown—the artifact she'd claimed from the Battleborn case—suddenly grew warm against her skin.
A voice spoke in her mind, ancient and commanding: Clear the path.
And suddenly, impossibly, Davinia could see it. A route through the flames. Places where the fire would part, where the smoke would clear, where safe passage could be made. The crown wasn't just showing her—it was creating the path.
"THERE!" she shouted, pointing. "Follow my voice! Straight ahead, then left!"
The fisherman, choking on smoke, followed her directions. He stumbled through exactly where she'd indicated, and the flames seemed to bend away from him, creating a corridor of safety that shouldn't have existed.
He emerged, coughing and burned but alive. The crowd cheered, and Davinia stood there, one hand on the crown, feeling the power still thrumming through it.
"That was incredible," Danica whispered, taking her hand. "How did you—"
"I don't know," Davinia said honestly. "But we should probably go before someone asks questions."
They made their way to the Lonely Troll, a dockside tavern that was significantly less grim in the daylight. They found a table by the window and ordered food that was surprisingly good.
"Thank you," Danica said after a while. "For bringing me here. For including me in all of this."
"I want you with me," Davinia said simply. "Always."
Their eyes met, and the world seemed to narrow to just the two of them, the noise of the tavern fading to distant background sounds.
The two women remained focused on each other. They missed the city guard investigating the burned section of dock. They missed when the guards pulled a charred, barely recognizable corpse from beneath the smoldering timbers.
THE MARKET
Kyboah woke early and restless. The events in Falkreath weighed on him—what he'd been forced to do to Davinia, the people they'd left behind, the compromises they'd made. He needed to move, to focus on something tangible.
The market district of Solitude was everything Falkreath's hadn't been—vibrant, prosperous, safe. He wandered between stalls, not looking for anything in particular, just letting his mind settle.
Then he saw it.
A small merchant's stall, tucked between a blacksmith and an alchemist. The proprietor was an elderly Nord woman, and her wares were a mix of antiques and curiosities. Most of it was junk—old helmets, tarnished jewelry, books with half the pages missing.
But on the back wall, hanging from a leather strap, was a shield.
It was ancient. The metal was pitted with age and the wooden backing cracked and warped, far too damaged for combat use. But that detail paled beside what caught his attention.
On the face of the shield, barely visible beneath centuries of tarnish, was a mark. A snowflake. Intricate, geometric, identical to the one on his enchanted gloves.
"You have a good eye," the merchant said, noticing his stare. "That's a museum piece, that is. Found it in a ruin up north years ago. The mark matches no modern Jarl's heraldry—I could never figure out what hold it came from."
"How much?" Kyboah asked.
"For that? Two hundred gold. It's an antique, you understand."
Kyboah paid without haggling. The shield was heavy in his hands, the leather strap brittle with age. But the mark... the mark was unmistakable.
"Where did you say you found this?" he asked.
"Didn't say specifically," the woman replied. "But it was in the ruins north of Winterhold. My husband was a treasure hunter, back in the day. Found all sorts of strange things up in those frozen wastes before the cold took him."
Winterhold. The same place where they'd found the gloves in the Pale Lady's tomb.
"Is there anyone in the city who might know more about this mark?" Kyboah asked. "A historian, perhaps?"
"The woman considered. "The Bards College would be your best bet. They've got texts on heraldry and ancient Nordic symbols going back to the Dragon Cult. If anyone can tell you what that snowflake means, it'll be them."
Kyboah thanked her and made his way to the Bards College, the shield strapped to his back alongside his pack.

The Bards College was alive with music and scholarly debate. Kyboah found himself directed to an instructor named Giraud Gemane, a Breton scholar who specialized in ancient Nordic history.
"Fascinating," Giraud said, examining the shield with obvious interest. "This symbol comes from no modern hold. It's far older. Pre-Alessian, I'd wager."
"What does it mean?" Kyboah asked.
"I'm uncertain of the exact meaning," Giraud admitted. "But I've seen similar geometric patterns associated with master artificers from the First Era. There was a tradition of smiths in ancient times who specialized in ice enchantments—creating armor and weapons that could withstand the worst of Skyrim's climate or harness the cold itself as a weapon."
He looked up from the shield. "If this symbol represents what I think it does, it's the mark of a particular master smith. A craftsman whose work was legendary even in their own time."
"Are there any records of where this smith might have worked?" Kyboah asked.
"The records here are incomplete," Orion said. "But the College of Winterhold would have more comprehensive archives on ancient Nordic artificers. If there are any records of this smith's location, they'd be there."
Kyboah filed that information away. Winterhold was where Seraleth had been headed before she'd joined them. Winterhold was where she'd been trained as a mage before switching to more practical combat skills. And now it seemed Winterhold held the key to understanding his gloves and this shield.
As he was leaving, he encountered Orion in the college's courtyard.
"Kyboah!" the Breton called out, waving. "Didn't expect to see you here."
"Research," Kyboah said, gesturing to the shield. "What about you?"
Orion grinned, and for a moment, he looked like his old self—before Falkreath, before the vampirism. "I'm enrolling. The war horn needs upgrading, and the college offers lessons in musical enchantments. Plus..." He lowered his voice. "If we're going to be the King's agents, it might be useful to have connections here. Bards hear things. They go everywhere, see everything. It's an intelligence network waiting to be tapped."
Kyboah had to admit, that was actually clever. "How much?"
"They wanted seven thousand gold," Orion said. "I talked them down to thirty-three hundred. Half tuition, considering I'm already an accomplished musician and just need the advanced courses."
They walked together back toward the market, Orion explaining his plans for improving the war horn with harmonic resonance enchantments. For a few minutes, normalcy returned—two companions discussing strategy and equipment, planning for the future.
The two of them avoided mentioning Falkreath. They avoided discussing what Orion had become, or what he'd done the night before.
The darkness held some things better than daylight.
THE TEMPLE
Saijah had felt uncomfortable since arriving in Solitude. The city was too big, too stone, too civilized. She missed the forests, the open sky, the feeling of leaves beneath her feet.
The only green space in the entire city, she discovered, was the Temple of the Divines—specifically, the small garden behind it where priests tended to a struggling sapling.
She found herself drawn there without quite knowing why.
The Gildergreen sapling was pitiful. It should have been thriving in the consecrated soil, should have been growing tall and proud as a symbol of Kynareth's blessing. Instead, it was dying, its leaves yellowed and spotted with rot, its bark peeling in places to reveal blackened wood beneath.
Saijah knelt beside it, one hand reaching out to touch the trunk.
The moment her fingers made contact, the world exploded.
Suddenly she was everywhere and nowhere. She could feel every tree in Skyrim—every pine, every birch, every flowering plant and creeping vine. They breathed as one great organism, connected through root and wind and the blessing of Kynareth herself.
And in that vast, living network, there was a cancer.
She could feel it, taste it, recognize it with a horror that made her gasp. The corruption that had infected Thornheart Grove was here. The rot that served Mehrunes Dagon, the Daedric Prince of destruction and natural disaster, had spread to Solitude.
Here. In Solitude. In the capital itself.
The Mythic Dawn cult had touched this tree, had tried to use it as an anchor for their corruption. They were here, in the city, working toward some purpose she couldn't quite grasp but could feel as a wrongness in the web of nature.
When she pulled her hand back, she was kneeling in the garden, tears streaming down her face. A priest had noticed her distress and was approaching with concern.
"Are you alright, child?" he asked.
"The tree," Saijah managed. "It's sick. Corrupted. Daedric magic."
The priest's expression shifted from concern to alarm. "How do you know this?"
"I can feel it," Saijah said, standing on shaky legs. "I can feel all of them. Every plant in Skyrim. Kynareth showed me this gift."
The priest studied her face, saw the truth there, and paled. "We must inform the High Priestess. If what you say is true—"
"It's true," Saijah said. "And whoever did this remains in the city, still working. This was just the beginning of something."
She left the temple in a daze, the sensation of connection still thrumming through her. She could feel the trees in the palace gardens, the vines growing on the city walls, the algae in the harbor. All of it was part of her now, or she was part of it.
The gift was overwhelming. And the knowledge of what lurked beneath it—the Mythic Dawn, here in the heart of Imperial power—was terrifying.
She made her way to the market in a fugue state, needing to ground herself in something practical. A weapon. New gear. Something tangible.
Fletcher, the Bosmer bowyer, had exactly what she needed. A glass bow, beautifully crafted, with the perfect draw weight and balance. It cost nearly everything she had, but the moment she held it, Saijah knew it was meant to be hers.
"You have the touch of the Green," Fletcher said quietly as she counted out her coin. "I can see it on you. Kynareth's blessing."
"Or her burden," Saijah replied.
Fletcher smiled sadly. "Often the same thing, child. Often the same thing."
CASTLE DOUR
Davinia stood outside Castle Dour, alone, staring at the grim fortress that served as Imperial military headquarters.
Legate Quintus had sent a runner to the inn earlier, requesting her presence for a private meeting before the evening's audience with the King. The message had been formal, professional, and impossible to refuse.
She'd left Danica at the Winking Skeever, promising to return soon. Now she stood before the gates, trying to calm the anxiety that coiled in her stomach.
This was her past. The Legion. The structure and discipline and unquestioning loyalty she'd walked away from. And now it was reaching out to pull her back.
The guards recognized her immediately—Quintus had clearly briefed them. They escorted her through the fortress, past training yards where soldiers drilled with mechanical precision, past armories and strategy rooms, to a private office overlooking the Sea of Ghosts.
General Tullius was waiting for her.
He was exactly as she remembered—stern, pragmatic, radiating authority. A man who'd dedicated his life to the Empire and couldn't understand why anyone wouldn't do the same.
"Davinia," he said, gesturing to a chair. "Sit. This won't take long."
She sat, back straight, hands folded in her lap. Old habits died hard.
"You've made quite a name for yourself," Tullius continued. "The Obsidian Lanterns. Impressive work in Riften and Falkreath. High King Torygg speaks highly of you."
"Thank you, sir."
"I'll get to the point. Your parents are coming to Skyrim."
Davinia's world stopped.
"What?" she managed.
"They've been assigned to my staff as strategic advisors. Your father's expertise in siege warfare and your mother's intelligence network are exactly what we need to end this rebellion." Tullius paused. "They'll be arriving within the month."
Davinia couldn't breathe. Her parents. Here. After years of carefully maintained distance, of letters that said nothing important, of a life built far away from their expectations and disappointments.
"I... I see," she said, though her voice sounded distant to her own ears.
Tullius was still talking. Something about the evening's audience, about the King's plans to create a new order of agents, about how they'd be relying on the Obsidian Lanterns going forward. Davinia heard none of it.
Her parents were coming to Skyrim.
"Can we count on you?" Tullius asked. "Once you're the King's agents, you'll be representing Skyrim itself. Your actions will have consequences far beyond your immediate missions."
"Yes," Davinia said automatically. "Yes, of course."
"Good." Tullius stood, the meeting clearly over. "Your audience is at sundown. Don't be late."
Davinia walked out of Castle Dour in a fog. She barely registered the walk back to the Winking Skeever, barely heard Danica's concerned questions.
Her parents. Here. Soon.
She'd built a new life. She'd found love, purpose, freedom. She'd become someone she could respect.
And now the past was coming to judge whether it was enough.
THE BLUE PALACE
Legate Quintus arrived at the Winking Skeever precisely an hour before sundown, his armor gleaming, his bearing immaculate.
"It's time," he said simply.
The party gathered—Kyboah with his ancient shield strapped to his back, Saijah still processing the overwhelming gift Kynareth had given her, Davinia struggling to focus on anything but her parents, Danica staying close to Davinia's side, Alfonso and Orion looking perfectly human thanks to their gorged state.
"Wait," Kyboah said, looking around. "Where's Ja'ha?"
They searched the inn. The old Khajiit's room was empty, her few possessions gone.
"She must have left during the night," Alfonso said, though his tone suggested he knew exactly where she'd gone.
They had no time to search for her. Quintus was already leading them through the streets toward the palace, and the sun was setting fast.
The Blue Palace was magnificent in the evening light. The marble seemed to glow from within, and the stained glass windows cast pools of colored light across the polished floors. Courtiers in fine silks moved through the halls with practiced grace, and stern Legionnaires stood at attention at every doorway.
They were led past the usual petitioners, past the court nobles who stared at them with open curiosity, directly to the throne room.
High King Torygg sat on his throne at the far end of the hall. He was young—startlingly young to hold such power—but there was a quiet authority in the way he held himself. Beside him stood General Tullius, face impassive.
But what caught their attention was the man standing before the throne.
He wore steel plate armor that had been maintained with meticulous care. His posture was relaxed but ready, the stance of someone who'd spent years in combat and survived. A magnificent sword hung at his hip, and his eyes—weary but sharp—swept over them with the assessing gaze of a true professional.
Torygg rose slightly. "Welcome, heroes. Your deeds have preceded you."
The party approached, and the warrior turned to face them fully. Up close, they could see the scars that marked his face and hands, the calluses of a man who'd wielded weapons more than words.
"I have heard tales of a frozen tomb in Winterhold," Torygg continued, "its curse broken by a group of determined adventurers. Of a corrupted grove near Riften, cleansed by their hand. And of darkness in Falkreath, driven back by their courage. You have proven you can work as one—a feat rarer than any magic."
He turned his gaze to the lone warrior. "And I have heard tales of a blade in the darkness who hunts the monsters that plague our lands. They call you the Ashen Blade. A man who has accomplished alone what most companies could not. Krusp Fanck."
The warrior nodded once. "It is good to meet you. The King spoke of your deeds. It is rare to find those who stand against the dark with such conviction."
His voice was low, calm, and surprisingly warm. Not what they'd expected from someone called "the Ashen Blade."
"I am Krusp Fanck. I am here because the High King asked it of me."
Before anyone could respond, General Tullius stepped forward.
"Your Majesty, with respect, I must voice my concerns." His skeptical eyes fixed on the party. "These... freelancers operate outside any command structure. Why should the Crown trust them with matters of state security when their only loyalty is to coin?"
The challenge hung in the air.
Kyboah opened his mouth to respond, but Davinia was faster.
"General Tullius," she said, her voice carrying clearly through the hall. "With respect, sir, we've never asked for trust based on promises. We've earned it through action."
She stepped forward, and something in her bearing made the entire court pay attention. The Legion training, perhaps, or simply the conviction of someone who'd been tested and hadn't broken.
"We broke a curse in the Pale Lady's tomb that had claimed dozens of lives. We saved a priestess from a corrupted heart-spirit and cleansed a sacred grove. In Whiterun, we exposed a murder plot that would have torn apart one of the city's founding families." She paused. "In Falkreath, we faced vampires. Ancient ones. We didn't run. We didn't negotiate for better pay. We went into their lair and we ended the threat."
She met Tullius's eyes directly. "Every person we've saved, every threat we've ended, we did because it was right. Not because we were ordered to. Not because we expected rewards. Because we could help, and so we did. That's the only loyalty that matters."
The silence that followed was absolute.
Then Tullius nodded slowly. "Your record speaks for itself. And your conviction is clear." He turned to Torygg. "Your Majesty, I withdraw my objection."
Davinia felt the tension in her shoulders ease slightly. They'd passed the first test.
"Thank you, General," Torygg said. He looked at the party with new interest. "I must attend to another matter briefly. In the meantime, please—enjoy the hospitality of my court."
THE WHISPERS
They found themselves released into the main hall of the palace, surrounded by nobles and courtiers who studied them with open curiosity.
Kyboah and Orion drifted toward the windows, content to observe. Saijah stayed close to Davinia, uncomfortable with the crowd. Alfonso moved through the space like a shadow, listening to conversations without seeming to.
But it was Davinia who drew the most attention. Perhaps it was her Legion bearing, or the way she'd spoken to General Tullius, but the nobles seemed to recognize her as someone worth talking to.
Jarl Elisif approached first, the High King's wife. She was beautiful in a fragile way, like porcelain stretched too thin.
"You're one of the Obsidian Lanterns," she said. It wasn't quite a question.
"Yes, my lady."
"I wanted to thank you," Elisif continued quietly. "For what you did in Whiterun. Olfrid Battle-Born is a friend. You saved his family from tearing itself apart." She paused, glancing toward where Torygg had disappeared. "My husband speaks often of you. Of what you represent."
"And what is that?" Davinia asked gently.
"Hope," Elisif said simply. "That there are still heroes in Skyrim. That the province can be saved without blood and civil war." Her voice dropped to barely a whisper. "He worries so much. About Ulfric. About the Stormcloaks. About whether he's strong enough to hold the kingdom together. I worry that he'll—"
She stopped herself, clearly having said more than she intended.
"He's a good king," Davinia said. "We can see that. And we'll do everything we can to help him."
Elisif squeezed her hand briefly. "Thank you. That means more than you know."
Across the room, a Thane named Erikur approached Kyboah with a friendly smile that didn't reach his eyes.
"You're the Khajiit, yes? The warrior?" He spoke too loudly, projecting to the nearby courtiers. "Tell me, what do you really think of our young king? Between us, of course."
Kyboah recognized the trap immediately. This man wanted him to say something negative, something that could be used against them later.
"I think," Kyboah said carefully, "that anyone who makes snap judgments about a king they've just met is a fool. And I'm not a fool."
Erikur's smile froze, then widened. "Well said! Quite right, quite right." He moved away, having learned nothing.
Another Thane—a woman named Bryling—approached Saijah.
"You have the look of someone who's been marked by the gods," she said bluntly. "I saw your face during the General's challenge. You understand what's really at stake here."
"What is at stake?" Saijah asked.
Bryling glanced around to ensure they weren't overheard. "Legitimacy. High King Torygg is young, untested in battle. Half the Jarls see him as weak—a boy playing at king. This isn't just about investigating dragons or supernatural threats. It's about proving he has the strength to command loyalty. Every deed you accomplish in his name strengthens his position. Every failure weakens it."
She met Saijah's eyes. "He's putting his faith in you. Don't let him down."
They mingled for perhaps thirty minutes, gathering pieces of the political puzzle. The Jarls were divided. The Thalmor were growing bolder. The civil war was a powder keg waiting for a spark.
And High King Torygg was trying to hold it all together through sheer force of will and the hope that heroism still mattered.
THE COURTYARD
A commotion outside drew their attention. Through the palace windows, they could see into the courtyard where three figures in golden armor had cornered a young Nord man.
Thalmor Justiciars.
"By the terms of the White-Gold Concordat," one of them was saying, his voice carrying clearly, "you are under arrest for the crime of Talos worship."
"I wasn't worshiping!" the boy protested. "I was just—"
"You were overheard invoking his name. That is sufficient evidence." The Justiciar's hand went to his sword. "You will come with us. Quietly."
The entire court had gone silent, watching through the windows. This was a test, Davinia realized. Torygg was watching to see what they would do.
She moved before thinking it through, striding toward the courtyard doors. The others followed immediately.
The Justiciars turned as they approached, golden eyes cold and dismissive.
"This does not concern you," one said.
"We are agents of High King Torygg," Davinia said, her voice carrying the authority she'd learned in the Legion. "And we need to speak with this young man about a matter of kingdom security."
It was a calculated lie, and the Justiciars knew it. But Davinia had invoked the King's name in his own palace, in front of his entire court. To refuse would be to publicly challenge Torygg's authority.
The lead Justiciar's jaw tightened. "The Concordat supersedes local law. Our authority comes from the Imperial City itself."
"Then perhaps," Alfonso said smoothly, stepping up beside Davinia, "you'd like to take that argument to General Tullius? I'm sure he'd be fascinated to hear the Thalmor explain why they're arresting citizens in the High King's own courtyard without consultation."
Behind them, Krusp Fanck had appeared. He said nothing, but his hand rested on Dawnbringer's hilt, and his presence radiated quiet menace. He would stand with them. Whatever came next, he would stand with them.
The Justiciars looked at each other. They were outnumbered, in hostile territory, and the entire court was watching. To press the issue would create a diplomatic incident.
"This matter is not concluded," the lead Justiciar said finally. "We will be reporting this interference to our superiors."
"Please do," Davinia replied.
They released the boy and departed, their golden armor catching the last rays of sunlight. The young Nord stood there, trembling, looking at Davinia with something close to worship.
"Thank you," he managed. "Thank you. I wasn't—I mean, I do honor Talos, but I wasn't trying to—"
"Go home," Davinia said gently. "Be more careful."
He fled.
The party returned to the throne room to find Torygg back on his throne, and his expression had changed. There was approval there, and something deeper. Respect.
"I witnessed what happened in the courtyard," he said without preamble. "You stood against the Thalmor. In my palace. For a boy you didn't know."
He stood, descending from his throne to address them as equals.
"That is the judgment I needed to see. Not blind obedience. Not calculated politics. The willingness to do what is right even when it's dangerous."
He turned to include Krusp as well. "Both of you. You stood together. That tells me everything I need to know."
THE CHARTER
"Skyrim is beset by shadows from within and without," Torygg said, his voice carrying through the throne room. "The Civil War is a wound that festers, but the return of dragons is a fire that threatens to consume us all. I cannot wait for a prophesied hero who may never come. I will act. We will act."
He gestured, and Falk Firebeard stepped forward with a heavy scroll case and several coin purses.
"I am creating a new order, loyal not to a faction or a hold, but to the very soul of Skyrim. You will be its founding members. You will be Skyrim's Wardens."
The title hung in the air, heavy with significance.
Torygg unrolled a magnificent parchment bearing the Great Seal of the High King. "This Royal Charter grants you the authority to act in my name. You may cross any hold's borders unimpeded, requisition reasonable aid from any Jarl's guard, and investigate any supernatural threat to the people of this land. You answer to me, and to me alone."
Falk Firebeard presented each of them with a heavy purse. Twelve hundred gold pieces—more money than most Nords saw in a year.
"This is not the pay of a mercenary, but the stipend of a royal agent," Torygg continued. "Your first mission as Wardens is to travel to Kynesgrove. We have received confirmed reports of a dragon attack. The village is devastated. I need you to investigate, assess the threat, and if it remains, end it. Be my eyes and ears. Return with the truth."
Krusp gave a single, sharp nod. "I accept the charter. The mission is clear. We should depart at once."
The party looked at each other, then at Torygg. This was real. This was happening. They were no longer just adventurers chasing coin and glory.
They were Wardens.
"We accept," Davinia said, speaking for all of them.
Torygg smiled, and for a moment, he looked less like a king and more like a young man who'd just been given hope.
"One final matter," he said. "The Wardens will need reliable, discreet transport."
He led them from the throne room, through the palace grounds to the royal stables. There, standing beside a familiar cart—now bearing new Imperial harnesses and the faint emblem of the Crown painted on its side—was Old Bjorn.
The old carter looked up from checking a horse's harness, and his weathered face broke into a genuine smile.
"Well, well," he said with a chuckle. "Can't say I'm surprised. Always knew you lot were destined for something more than clearing out bandit camps. Looks like our arrangement just got a bit more official."
"Bjorn's reputation for discretion and knowledge of the roads is legendary," Torygg explained. "The Crown has officially retained his services. He is now your dedicated transport, his salary and expenses paid from the royal treasury. His service is to the Wardens exclusively."
Bjorn turned to Krusp, extending a weathered hand. "Don't believe we've met. The name's Bjorn. I'll be getting you where you need to go."
Krusp took the hand, his grip firm and professional. "Krusp Fanck. So long as you are reliable, we will have no problems."
Bjorn just grinned. "Don't you worry about that. Now," he said, turning back to the party, "I hear we're heading to Kynesgrove. Best get loaded up. It's a long road."
They spent the next hour making preparations. The stipend allowed them to purchase final supplies, and the charter opened doors that had been closed. When they mentioned they were Wardens, merchants fell over themselves to provide quality goods at fair prices.
By the time night fell properly, they were ready. Almost.
"We should get some sleep," Kyboah said. "Leave at first light."
The others agreed, and they made their way back to the Winking Skeever. The vampires among them were careful to keep their hoods up, their enhanced nature hidden from casual observation.
But Orion had one more piece of business to attend to.
A BLADE IN THE DARK
Orion waited until the others had retired to their rooms. Then he slipped out of the inn, moving through the midnight streets of Solitude with purpose.
The summons had come earlier, delivered by a street urchin with a note that simply read: "Hall of the Dead. Midnight. Come alone."
He'd known immediately what it was. The Dark Brotherhood. They'd been watching him. And now they wanted to see what he could do.
The Hall of the Dead was empty at this hour, the priests having retired for the night. Orion moved through the main chamber to the catacombs beyond, following the faint light of a single candle.
A figure emerged from the shadows behind a sarcophagus. An Argonian in black-and-red shrouded armor, his eyes reflecting the candlelight like a predator's.
"You were wise to come alone," the Argonian said, his voice a low hiss. "We have been watching you. The shadows whisper of what you have become." His gaze flickered over Orion's features, seeing past the human facade to the vampire beneath. "A useful tool, if you have the will to wield it."
"What do you want?" Orion asked.
"Your test is simple. And it is here. Now."
Vasha—for that had to be who this was—led him deeper into the catacombs, to a barred grate overlooking a larger burial chamber below. The space was well-lit by caged torches, and three people moved within it.
"Down there are three people," Vasha explained. "A disgraced Legionnaire captain, a bandit chief, and a failed mage apprentice. We... acquired them. They are unarmed. They believe they are in a holding cell, waiting for a ransom that will never come."
He pointed to the mage, a young man huddled in a corner, clearly terrified.
"That one is your target. The contract is for the mage only. The other two are the test. The Legionnaire is a trained soldier, her senses are sharp. The bandit is a paranoid brute, he trusts no one. You are to be a ghost. A whisper in the dark."
Vasha's reptilian eyes gleamed. "Enter that room. Kill the mage. Do not be seen by the other two. If they spot you, if they scream, you have failed. Vanish as silently as you arrived. We will be watching."
Orion studied the chamber below. The rafters and catwalks that crisscrossed the upper level. The positions of the torches. The patrol pattern of the Legionnaire. The nervous pacing of the bandit.
Then Valerius's voice whispered in his mind, cold and amused: A proper test of subtlety. Do not just kill him. Terrify them. Let the soldier and the bandit feel a cold dread, a presence they cannot see. Turn this silent murder into a legend. Impress me.
Orion smiled in the darkness.
He moved to the grate and dropped down silently, landing in a crouch on one of the upper catwalks. Below, the three prisoners continued their uneasy movements, unaware.
The first thing he did was extinguish the lights.
His hands moved in precise patterns, ice magic flowing from his fingers. The caged torches began to frost over, the flames sputtering and dying one by one. Within thirty seconds, the chamber was plunged into near-total darkness, lit only by the faint glow of distant torches in the corridor beyond.
"What the—" the bandit started.
"Quiet," the Legionnaire hissed. "Something's wrong."
In the darkness above them, Orion moved to the next phase. He gathered his ice magic again, but this time he used it differently. He compressed it, rubbed it together, created friction and resonance in the frozen air itself.
The sound that resulted was horrible—a high-pitched squeal like metal scraping on ice, like the death cry of something frozen and tortured. It echoed through the chamber, seeming to come from everywhere and nowhere.
"What is that?" the bandit shouted, his voice rising with panic.
"There!" the Legionnaire said, pointing toward the far corner where the sound seemed loudest. "Something's over there!"
They moved toward the sound, leaving their positions. The mage stayed huddled in his corner, too terrified to move.
Orion dropped from the ceiling like a falling shadow.
He landed on the mage with perfect precision, one hand clamping over the young man's mouth to prevent any scream. The other hand drove his sword into the mage's arm, pinning it to the stone floor, while simultaneously his free hand cast ice magic directly into the mage's open mouth, freezing his throat shut.
The mage's eyes went wide with terror and pain, but no sound emerged. He couldn't scream. Couldn't breathe. Could only stare up at the vampire above him.
Orion killed him quickly, efficiently, with a blade across the throat. Then he got to work.
Valerius wanted theater? He'd give him theater.
The body came apart with surgical precision. An arm here. A leg there. The torso arranged just so. By the time he was finished, the mage's remains were spread across the corner in an abstract pattern that would have looked at home in a mad artist's gallery.
The bandit and the Legionnaire were still investigating the far corner, arguing in hushed voices about what they'd heard.
Orion climbed back into the rafters, moving silently across the beams. As he reached the grate that led back to Vasha's position, he cast one final spell.
Magelight bloomed above the mage's desecrated corpse, bright and sudden, illuminating the horror in stark detail.
The Legionnaire and the bandit turned. Saw. The bandit screamed. The Legionnaire stood frozen, her professional composure shattering.
And then Orion was gone, slipping back through the grate and into the darkness beyond, leaving them trapped in the chamber with a corpse and the knowledge that something inhuman had been there with them.

Vasha was waiting in the main chamber, his expression unreadable.
"A true ghost," he said finally. "Silent. Efficient. And theatrical. You understood the assignment on multiple levels."
He produced a bundle wrapped in black cloth. "The Night Mother is pleased. Welcome to the Brotherhood, Brother Orion."
The bundle contained shrouded armor—light, flexible, enchanted for silence and shadow. The armor of a true assassin.
"Your first contract will come soon," Vasha said. "Until then, continue your other work. The Brotherhood values members who can move in both worlds—the shadow and the light."
Orion accepted the armor, feeling its weight. This was real. He'd joined the Dark Brotherhood. He was an assassin now, as well as a vampire, as well as a Warden.
In Valerius's voice, cold approval: You are a worthy asset.
Orion returned to the Winking Skeever as dawn approached, the shrouded armor hidden in his pack, the memory of the mage's terrified eyes still fresh in his mind.
He didn't feel guilty. He didn't feel proud. He felt... nothing. Just the cold satisfaction of a job well done and the knowledge that he was becoming something new.
Something dangerous.
MORNING DEPARTURE
Dawn broke over Solitude, bright and clear. The party gathered in the courtyard of the Winking Skeever, their gear packed, their new charter sealed in waterproof cases.
Bjorn had the cart ready, the horses fresh and eager. Krusp was already seated in the back, his armor polished, Dawnbringer resting across his knees.
"Kynesgrove," Bjorn said, checking the harnesses one final time. "Three days' travel if the weather holds. Four if it doesn't."
They loaded their gear, settling in for the journey. Alfonso and Orion looked perfectly human in the morning light, their feeding the night before sustaining them. Saijah sat quietly, still processing the overwhelming connection to nature that Kynareth had granted her. Kyboah kept the ancient shield close, its snowflake mark a mystery he intended to solve.
Davinia sat beside Danica, their hands intertwined, both of them trying not to think about what waited at the end of this journey. Dragons. And after that, whatever came next.
As the cart rolled out of Solitude's gates, heading east toward Kynesgrove and destiny, none of them looked back.
Behind them, the city continued its morning routines, unaware that three of its citizens had vanished in the night—a Dunmer woman, a homeless man, and a young mage apprentice. Unaware that the vampires who'd killed them were now official agents of the Crown.
Unaware that the King they trusted had just placed the fate of Skyrim in the hands of heroes who were becoming monsters.
The road ahead was long, and dragons waited at the end of it.
But for now, in the bright morning light, with purpose and authority and the weight of a kingdom's hope on their shoulders, the Obsidian Lanterns—now Skyrim's Wardens—traveled east.
Whatever came next, they would face it together.
Most of them, anyway.

